WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.470
&gt;&gt; I'd like to welcome Rick Moonen from Las
Vegas, R M Seafood, and also on this season's

00:00:06.470 --> 00:00:11.170
"Top Chef Masters," which I'm sure hopefully
he'll want to talk about.

00:00:11.170 --> 00:00:15.349
So Rick, if you don't mind, I'll give the
floor to you.

00:00:15.349 --> 00:00:16.349
Thanks for coming here.

00:00:16.349 --> 00:00:18.289
Rick Moonen: All right. It's a pleasure.
I'm thrilled to be here. Thank you very much.

00:00:18.289 --> 00:00:19.289
&gt;&gt; [Clapping]

00:00:19.289 --> 00:00:24.289
Rick Moonen: Thanks for coming in and listening
to me talk at you today a little bit.

00:00:24.289 --> 00:00:30.050
I've got about 45 minutes to just give you
a little bit of "The World According to Me"

00:00:30.050 --> 00:00:34.969
in the world of seafood.
And then, we'll have like some 15 minutes

00:00:34.969 --> 00:00:38.219
or so to just Q and A.
Talk about anything.

00:00:38.219 --> 00:00:43.949
So I'm going to briefly touch on some subjects
that I can talk about for hours, but that's

00:00:43.949 --> 00:00:46.999
not why I'm here.
I'm just kind of like giving you an idea.

00:00:46.999 --> 00:00:51.569
I wrote a cookbook last year called, "Fish,
Without a Doubt.”

00:00:51.569 --> 00:00:56.149
And the reason for "Without A Doubt" is because,
there's so many confusions around seafood.

00:00:56.149 --> 00:00:58.690
I've been in the hospitality industry for
30 years.

00:00:58.690 --> 00:01:05.150
So, I've seen a lot of changes.
I've seen a lot of advances.

00:01:05.150 --> 00:01:08.100
And we're at a critical point of our lives
right now that, if we don't do something,

00:01:08.100 --> 00:01:11.370
or understand a lot more about our oceans,
we could lose our oceans, right?

00:01:11.370 --> 00:01:13.360
That's the truth of it all, and that's the
scary part.

00:01:13.360 --> 00:01:17.970
And I hope that it scares people enough to
motivate them to take some action.

00:01:17.970 --> 00:01:21.870
And that's my ulterior motive today is to
kind of like, leave you with that feeling

00:01:21.870 --> 00:01:26.250
that, "Holy Smokes. This isn't an option anymore.
It's a call to arms."

00:01:26.250 --> 00:01:31.610
I'm going to give you a little bit of my bio
 -- a little verbal bio of myself.

00:01:31.610 --> 00:01:35.540
I graduated from the Culinary Institute of
America, which was -- and still is -- considered

00:01:35.540 --> 00:01:42.820
one of the best schools in the world for culinary
arts, learning about cooking.

00:01:42.820 --> 00:01:47.620
Graduated first in my class in 1978.
That's a long time ago, and the world was

00:01:47.620 --> 00:01:50.550
different then.
I went into New York City, and I worked at

00:01:50.550 --> 00:01:54.810
a restaurant called, "La Cote Basque." from
1980 to '82.

00:01:54.810 --> 00:01:57.500
I was there for two years.
I was the Saucier.

00:01:57.500 --> 00:02:01.520
Saucier is just like this very big position.
You're in charge of all the stocks, the sauces,

00:02:01.520 --> 00:02:07.140
sauteeing everything on the line.
And as it would just -- I was cooking meat,

00:02:07.140 --> 00:02:09.399
actually, I was on the stage where I really
cooked meat.

00:02:09.399 --> 00:02:13.819
On the other end of the line was a chef called
Charlie Palmer, who is pretty well-known today.

00:02:13.819 --> 00:02:16.650
And he was cooking fish.
And as it turns out, he's got the meat restaurant,

00:02:16.650 --> 00:02:19.780
I got the fish restaurant, but that's just
the way it was back then.

00:02:19.780 --> 00:02:24.049
I went to Key West, Florida, after that, because
I wanted to see something out of New York

00:02:24.049 --> 00:02:25.049
City.
That's where I grew up.

00:02:25.049 --> 00:02:30.079
I grew up in a part of the suburb of New York
called Flushing, which was really -- in the

00:02:30.079 --> 00:02:33.849
60's and the 70's, when I was growing up -- was
a really melting pot.

00:02:33.849 --> 00:02:39.819
There was a lot of ethnic diversity.
You know, across the street from me was the

00:02:39.819 --> 00:02:44.849
Greek family.
Then, there was Catholics and Jews and Italians

00:02:44.849 --> 00:02:48.409
and Irish, and you name it, it was all in
the same neighborhood.

00:02:48.409 --> 00:02:51.139
And there was traditions that went along with
it.

00:02:51.139 --> 00:02:54.989
So it was a pretty cool place for me to grow
up as far as learning about diversity of the

00:02:54.989 --> 00:03:00.450
world, you know, if you were going to be in
one area.

00:03:00.450 --> 00:03:02.490
So I wanted to leave.
So I went down to Key West, Florida.

00:03:02.490 --> 00:03:05.090
I stayed down there for nine months.
I went fishing a lot.

00:03:05.090 --> 00:03:07.930
I worked in a restaurant.
There was a lot of seafood down there, and

00:03:07.930 --> 00:03:13.680
I saw a lot about what freshness really meant.
I would have guys -- shrimpers -- come to

00:03:13.680 --> 00:03:17.870
my back door with bags of mixed-size shrimps
that they just caught that day, selling it

00:03:17.870 --> 00:03:21.069
for five dollars a pound just so they could
have some drinking money.

00:03:21.069 --> 00:03:27.310
It was an education for me, but it was also
an exposure to real, super-pristine freshness.

00:03:27.310 --> 00:03:31.499
Went back to New York City after being in
Key West for nine months, because I realized

00:03:31.499 --> 00:03:37.040
New York was really the place to be.
And I got a job at Le Cirque, another very

00:03:37.040 --> 00:03:42.409
well-known, high-end French restaurant.
Because when I got out of school, it was French.

00:03:42.409 --> 00:03:46.090
There wasn't American restaurants.
There wasn't a lot of diversity.

00:03:46.090 --> 00:03:52.200
Cuisine was considered -- if you wanted to
go into a great training experience -- it

00:03:52.200 --> 00:03:55.510
was the French restaurants.
And there was a lot of them.

00:03:55.510 --> 00:04:01.209
And that slowly evolved into what we see of
more cross-cultural and more ethnic-focused

00:04:01.209 --> 00:04:05.879
restaurants in neighborhoods in New York City.
Stayed at Le Cirque for two years.

00:04:05.879 --> 00:04:11.769
I was the Saucier there as well.
Went on to a couple of other smaller restaurants

00:04:11.769 --> 00:04:13.889
from there.
Le Relais, French restaurant where I had my

00:04:13.889 --> 00:04:17.550
first chef job.
It was a small bistro, bustling, busy.

00:04:17.550 --> 00:04:20.940
Went in the kitchen, just worked like crazy
and just tried to make sense of it all.

00:04:20.940 --> 00:04:24.560
Worked at a place called Bar Louie.
Consulted that.

00:04:24.560 --> 00:04:29.430
Got them set up with their -- it was a large
restaurant down by the NYU, a University in

00:04:29.430 --> 00:04:33.100
New York City.
And they were bustling.

00:04:33.100 --> 00:04:37.210
It was an Italian restaurant, and I set up
all the sauces and the systems and everything.

00:04:37.210 --> 00:04:42.110
Eventually went to my own restaurant called
Chelsea Central.

00:04:42.110 --> 00:04:45.840
My first review from the New York Times was
a two-star review from Brian Miller who was

00:04:45.840 --> 00:04:51.170
the reviewer at the time.
It was a turning point for my career, because

00:04:51.170 --> 00:04:56.020
you really 'den, den, den,' all of a sudden
celebrity started to get involved.

00:04:56.020 --> 00:04:59.170
Because when I went to school, it was just
a -- it was a profession.

00:04:59.170 --> 00:05:02.470
It was a vocation.
You were working 12 hours a day, six days

00:05:02.470 --> 00:05:09.870
of the week, and you really weren't getting
any kind of special recognition for it.

00:05:09.870 --> 00:05:13.561
But when I finally went to The Water Club,
things started to change a little bit.

00:05:13.561 --> 00:05:18.480
This is a little more than 20 years ago.
It was 1988 when I started.

00:05:18.480 --> 00:05:22.180
I started on 8/8/88, as a matter of fact.
Yesterday was 9/9/09, so.

00:05:22.180 --> 00:05:28.270
This is one of those dates I could remember.
And I stayed there for four years.

00:05:28.270 --> 00:05:32.860
And during that time frame, I got involved,
not only -- I started to put on different

00:05:32.860 --> 00:05:35.250
hats.
I started to see some changes, some shifts.

00:05:35.250 --> 00:05:38.170
People started to ask more questions.
You weren't just a cuisineer anymore.

00:05:38.170 --> 00:05:43.210
You needed to know more about people's diets.
You know, because you had the Atkin's Diet.

00:05:43.210 --> 00:05:47.471
If your guests were asking you, you know,
they told you they were on the Atkin's Diet,

00:05:47.471 --> 00:05:50.420
you were expected to know what that meant
and how you were going to feed them, and what

00:05:50.420 --> 00:05:54.870
on the menu didn't conform to the Atkin's
Diet, or this diet, or that diet.

00:05:54.870 --> 00:05:58.370
And then there was the need to learn a little
bit more about the environment.

00:05:58.370 --> 00:06:02.890
How things were caught.
Sourcing of food became more of a focus because

00:06:02.890 --> 00:06:06.440
of media, knowledge, you know, education of
the consumer.

00:06:06.440 --> 00:06:15.740
I started to realize that the tuna that they're
purchasing or consuming is affecting dolphins,

00:06:15.740 --> 00:06:17.640
you know.
So they wanted to know how it was caught.

00:06:17.640 --> 00:06:22.150
And so, now you had to start to source out
a little bit with more information so that

00:06:22.150 --> 00:06:26.540
you could provide your guests, who come to
your restaurant, with the certain level of

00:06:26.540 --> 00:06:30.610
trust that you're going to take care of them,
and that you can answer these questions.

00:06:30.610 --> 00:06:36.410
So the role of the chef definitely went through
an evolution during that time frame, and I

00:06:36.410 --> 00:06:42.550
got involved as an activist and an environmentalist
when I started speaking out about genetically-engineered

00:06:42.550 --> 00:06:46.160
foods.
That was 20 years ago.

00:06:46.160 --> 00:06:51.230
And I was interviewed, by happenstance, when
I was with a group of chefs on the steps of

00:06:51.230 --> 00:06:55.340
City Hall.
And a gentleman with a microphone asked me

00:06:55.340 --> 00:07:00.280
if I would make a comment about genetically-engineered
foods, and I'm like, "What's that?”

00:07:00.280 --> 00:07:01.850
You know, I'm hanging out with a bunch of
other chefs.

00:07:01.850 --> 00:07:06.860
We're dressed up in chef jackets because we're
getting our picture taken because of our contribution

00:07:06.860 --> 00:07:11.840
the increase of tourism in New York City.
And so, I get this microphone put in my face,

00:07:11.840 --> 00:07:16.090
and he's telling me that, "Well, genetically
engineered foods is where they're taking,

00:07:16.090 --> 00:07:23.060
you know, fruits and vegetables and they're
changing them and altering them with the genes

00:07:23.060 --> 00:07:29.000
of other animals and bacteria etc. to alter
them so that they can give them longer shelf-lives

00:07:29.000 --> 00:07:33.800
etc.”
And I was like, "Wow, that's pretty radical."

00:07:33.800 --> 00:07:36.470
So I made a comment.
I said, "Hi. My name's Rick Moonen.

00:07:36.470 --> 00:07:39.670
I'm the executive chef at The Water Club.
I think Mother Nature has been doing a terrific

00:07:39.670 --> 00:07:42.970
job for a millennium, and really, if we're
going to spend our money, we should put it

00:07:42.970 --> 00:07:47.521
best spent in distribution of really, good
organic foods, because it just didn't seem

00:07:47.521 --> 00:07:50.220
to make it into too many people's houses.
Thank you.”

00:07:50.220 --> 00:07:54.370
That made it on the radio, and it was one
of those radio stations that repeated a sound

00:07:54.370 --> 00:07:56.500
bite every hour.
And so, all of a sudden I'm getting phone

00:07:56.500 --> 00:07:59.790
calls from something I knew nothing about
a few hours ago, genetically engineered foods.

00:07:59.790 --> 00:08:04.481
So I'm suddenly the expert to go to.
So I realize at that point I needed to find

00:08:04.481 --> 00:08:07.830
out more.
And this is, again, in the late eighties.

00:08:07.830 --> 00:08:10.580
So the only thing you had was a fax machine
and a phone.

00:08:10.580 --> 00:08:14.030
You know, we didn't have all these things
on our laps.

00:08:14.030 --> 00:08:18.160
And I made a few phone calls.
I got the New York Times, looked up a genetically-engineered

00:08:18.160 --> 00:08:24.889
food article, and I realized that Dr. Rebecca
Goldberg and this guy named -- Oh, what was

00:08:24.889 --> 00:08:28.430
his name?
He was a big activist.

00:08:28.430 --> 00:08:32.880
Jeremy Rifkin! Big activist in D.C.
Called him up and said, "I need more information.”

00:08:32.880 --> 00:08:36.430
They faxed me a ream of paper.
And I'm sitting there reading and just wigging

00:08:36.430 --> 00:08:40.890
out over the fact that there's no premarket
safety testing on these things.

00:08:40.890 --> 00:08:44.150
There's flounder genes in your tomatoes, whether
you know it or not, because flounders are

00:08:44.150 --> 00:08:47.170
found that they can freeze, and they can thaw
out.

00:08:47.170 --> 00:08:51.060
A flounder will live. "Oh, that's cool.
Let's take that gene, put it in a tomato,

00:08:51.060 --> 00:08:54.560
and now we got frost-resistant tomatoes.”
[low whistle] Whoo.

00:08:54.560 --> 00:08:58.141
20 years later, we got Food Incorporated going
on in our lives.

00:08:58.141 --> 00:09:03.120
And it's scary, you know?
But back then, I was realizing that no pre-market

00:09:03.120 --> 00:09:07.070
safety testing, no mandatory labeling.
So I can't even find out if I'm getting it

00:09:07.070 --> 00:09:10.711
or not as a food product.
So I spoke out about it.

00:09:10.711 --> 00:09:14.061
And I ended up talking to a bunch of chefs.
We ended up having a press conference.

00:09:14.061 --> 00:09:18.250
The press conference turned into a Chef's
Coalition for the Pure Food Campaign.

00:09:18.250 --> 00:09:21.800
Five hundred chefs later, you know, a few
months later, sending out letters.

00:09:21.800 --> 00:09:26.380
Everybody's up in arms about their food, where
it's coming from, how they can't answer the

00:09:26.380 --> 00:09:30.350
concerns of their customers anymore, because
if you had an analogy to a flounder, how would

00:09:30.350 --> 00:09:33.430
I know if you were having a tomato salad today?
I can't tell you that anymore.

00:09:33.430 --> 00:09:36.040
That was just wrong, and that's really what
we're reacting to.

00:09:36.040 --> 00:09:40.820
I'm a chef.
But somehow I ended up becoming more than

00:09:40.820 --> 00:09:44.930
that.
Then I went from The Water Club to a restaurant

00:09:44.930 --> 00:09:50.540
called Oceana where my life went Boof.
Single subject. Seafood restaurant.

00:09:50.540 --> 00:09:54.920
Had lots of experience. Been in Key West.
Went fishing. Went fishing with my dad.

00:09:54.920 --> 00:09:57.960
Went to the Culinary Institute of America.
Graduated first in my class.

00:09:57.960 --> 00:10:03.560
I've got all the right things going on.
Now I've got the single subject of the oceanic

00:10:03.560 --> 00:10:08.150
world, Oceana.
And I got a phone call from Nora Pouillon,

00:10:08.150 --> 00:10:12.180
who's the chef that has an all-organic restaurant
in D.C.

00:10:12.180 --> 00:10:17.110
We had done things together, talking on panels
about genetically-engineered foods.

00:10:17.110 --> 00:10:22.839
And she got involved in a program called,
"Give Swordfish a Break.”

00:10:22.839 --> 00:10:27.190
Now, swordfish -- North Atlantic swordfish
 -- beautiful animal, pelagic, goes all over

00:10:27.190 --> 00:10:31.520
the world.
And if they'd found out, or they did some

00:10:31.520 --> 00:10:37.810
statistics, some studies, that if we don't
change the way we were buying North Atlantic

00:10:37.810 --> 00:10:40.020
swordfish, purchasing and catching it -- or,
hunting it, really.

00:10:40.020 --> 00:10:43.940
It's not just catching, it's hunting -- that
it was going to become commercially extinct

00:10:43.940 --> 00:10:46.170
in the next five years.
I was like, "Woe.”

00:10:46.170 --> 00:10:49.300
And because I was going to the Fulton Fish
Market on a regular basis when I was a chef

00:10:49.300 --> 00:10:54.220
at The Water Club, I realized that there were
some major changes from my own personal experience.

00:10:54.220 --> 00:10:59.110
I'd seen -- when I was at the Fulton Fish
Market -- the size of the fish diminish.

00:10:59.110 --> 00:11:02.660
They categorize them.
Swordfish that's under a hundred pounds is

00:11:02.660 --> 00:11:06.100
called a "pup."
Between 100 pounds and 200 pounds, it's called

00:11:06.100 --> 00:11:11.670
a "marker.”
Two hundred and above, it's a "double marker.”

00:11:11.670 --> 00:11:14.430
And on and on.
I'm going to guess that at 300 or above, it's

00:11:14.430 --> 00:11:18.170
probably a "triple marker.”
Now, I used to see double markers all the

00:11:18.170 --> 00:11:19.350
time.
I used to purchase them.

00:11:19.350 --> 00:11:21.480
You know, when I was at The Water Club, we
did some major volume.

00:11:21.480 --> 00:11:25.640
I'd buy entire fish.
It was a great steak on a grill for large

00:11:25.640 --> 00:11:30.550
parties, banquets.
Grilled swordfish was very, very, very well-appreciated.

00:11:30.550 --> 00:11:34.640
I started seeing smaller and smaller.
I mean, to the point where, it was more common

00:11:34.640 --> 00:11:37.750
on the Fulton Fish Market to find pups, 100
pounds and lower.

00:11:37.750 --> 00:11:43.000
And when I was asked to be a part of, "Give
Swordfish a Break," well, I saw that there

00:11:43.000 --> 00:11:45.320
was concern, so I joined.
I said, "Why not?”

00:11:45.320 --> 00:11:48.990
And I ended up becoming a poster-child spokesperson
for it.

00:11:48.990 --> 00:11:58.860
And I never looked back. You know.
What it was, was an awareness campaign to

00:11:58.860 --> 00:12:04.370
alert people that, "If we kind of lay off
of this fish a little bit? It'll make a recovery.”

00:12:04.370 --> 00:12:07.720
But it was more so trying to get government
regulations to happen.

00:12:07.720 --> 00:12:13.899
In the history of these regulatory agencies
trying to be persuaded to do the right thing,

00:12:13.899 --> 00:12:20.110
they normally -- it was difficult.
Whereas with this nationwide awareness program,

00:12:20.110 --> 00:12:25.470
motivated agencies to actually make regulatory
changes internationally.

00:12:25.470 --> 00:12:32.370
And North Atlantic swordfish became on a path
of sustainability, which is amazing and it

00:12:32.370 --> 00:12:38.630
was historic.
I ended up going from Oceana, after I got

00:12:38.630 --> 00:12:41.502
involved with "Give Swordfish a Break," I
went and opened up my own restaurant in New

00:12:41.502 --> 00:12:45.040
York City.
And now I'm in Sin City, Nevada -- Las Vegas,

00:12:45.040 --> 00:12:47.990
Nevada -- for the last five years, running
my own restaurant.

00:12:47.990 --> 00:12:52.040
It's called Rick Moonen's RM Seafood.
And it's about all different kinds of layers.

00:12:52.040 --> 00:12:57.690
From downstairs as a casual cafe where there's
recognizable seafood items like gumbos and

00:12:57.690 --> 00:13:01.830
chowders.
We have a sushi area. I have a raw bar area.

00:13:01.830 --> 00:13:07.150
And upstairs is my fine dining floor, where
the white tablecloths, the fancy linen and

00:13:07.150 --> 00:13:16.920
silver come out, and we deliver a topnotch,
expensive, high-end experience.

00:13:16.920 --> 00:13:24.240
When I graduated from The Culinary Institute
in '78, there was not a part of that -- and

00:13:24.240 --> 00:13:29.640
this is considered the finest culinary school
in the United States -- there wasn't even

00:13:29.640 --> 00:13:33.820
a program on seafood.
In 1976 when I started there, it wasn't a

00:13:33.820 --> 00:13:36.890
part of the curriculum.
There was nothing about fabrication of fish.

00:13:36.890 --> 00:13:43.520
There wasn't anything about product identification.
Because seafood is confusing to most people.

00:13:43.520 --> 00:13:51.910
And there's many, many reasons why it's confusing.
I was not really capable of finding too much

00:13:51.910 --> 00:13:56.390
sources on seafood, you know?
I'm thinking about back on, you know, you

00:13:56.390 --> 00:14:01.649
go through an entire culinary school, and
the only exposure that you had to seafood

00:14:01.649 --> 00:14:05.110
was from appetizers.
And that's really all that was being offered

00:14:05.110 --> 00:14:08.620
in restaurants at the time.
I have a couple of menus.

00:14:08.620 --> 00:14:14.520
This is a menu from Chicago in the 1970s.
And just for the heck of it before I came

00:14:14.520 --> 00:14:17.940
out here, I decided to open it up and look
at it, because I just wanted to know in the

00:14:17.940 --> 00:14:21.709
70's, what was being offered in restaurants.
And this isn't necessarily a seafood restaurant,

00:14:21.709 --> 00:14:27.940
but really, what you would have is shrimp
cocktail, crabmeat cocktail, smoked Nova Scotia

00:14:27.940 --> 00:14:35.750
salmon, baked clams, clams in red sauce.
You know, you would find dishes that were

00:14:35.750 --> 00:14:40.839
just very, very basic.
You weren't -- and back in that time that's

00:14:40.839 --> 00:14:44.320
when fish had -- and dishes had -- names to
them.

00:14:44.320 --> 00:14:48.750
You knew what "florentine" was.
Florentine meant that there was spinach in

00:14:48.750 --> 00:14:53.060
it.
I've got a list of things here.

00:14:53.060 --> 00:14:56.291
Bonn femme.
These are classic dishes.

00:14:56.291 --> 00:14:59.300
This is what you learned.
But it was only like five or six or seven

00:14:59.300 --> 00:15:01.930
different types of things that you learned
and that was it.

00:15:01.930 --> 00:15:06.450
Diversity of what was being served in the
United States was very narrow.

00:15:06.450 --> 00:15:12.970
You knew that "almondine" meant almonds.
A la Genevoise. If something was sauteed genevoise,

00:15:12.970 --> 00:15:15.959
it meant that there was going to be capers
and lemon and croutons, and maybe a little

00:15:15.959 --> 00:15:19.180
bit of brown sauce around the outside.
Florentine was spinach.

00:15:19.180 --> 00:15:25.200
You had Thermador, Rockefeller, Veronique,
and maybe that was about it.

00:15:25.200 --> 00:15:33.690
Those were recognizable names.
You didn't really find anything that was being

00:15:33.690 --> 00:15:39.000
innovatively handled.
And that started to happen.

00:15:39.000 --> 00:15:44.670
I guess it took maybe another 10, 15 years
before you started to see on menus things

00:15:44.670 --> 00:15:50.480
like this.
You know, poached Ecuadoran shrimp, arugula

00:15:50.480 --> 00:15:55.870
roasted baby beets, lime ginger vinaigrette.
You started to see more focus on products.

00:15:55.870 --> 00:16:04.190
You know, "day boat diver sea scallops seared
with," you know, and then they'll tell you

00:16:04.190 --> 00:16:07.040
the farm that the corn came from and how it
was done.

00:16:07.040 --> 00:16:13.870
And that became more of the norm on a menu.
So you went from classic dishes that you understood

00:16:13.870 --> 00:16:18.830
and moved into more of a innovative style
of dealing with the ocean.

00:16:18.830 --> 00:16:23.990
But there was still confusion, and why?
First of all, names.

00:16:23.990 --> 00:16:27.540
The nomenclature, or the "name game," I call
it.

00:16:27.540 --> 00:16:32.410
You know, just common names of fish just don't
exist.

00:16:32.410 --> 00:16:37.310
You can change the name any given day, any
given moment.

00:16:37.310 --> 00:16:40.110
The U.S. sea robin, for instance.
This is a nuisance fish.

00:16:40.110 --> 00:16:43.020
If you're out at sea fishing, you get sea
robins and you throw them back.

00:16:43.020 --> 00:16:45.529
They're junk fish.
They're a pain in the neck. They're taking

00:16:45.529 --> 00:16:48.860
your bait.
But basically, that same fish -- same genus

00:16:48.860 --> 00:16:52.450
and species -- is one of the bases for bouillon
base in France.

00:16:52.450 --> 00:16:58.800
It's just about confusion and misunderstanding.
Black fish. When I was at Oceana, I popularized

00:16:58.800 --> 00:17:00.900
a dish.
It was made out of a local fish out of Long

00:17:00.900 --> 00:17:03.269
Island.
It was called tautog, or black fish.

00:17:03.269 --> 00:17:07.179
But anybody that would fish it in Long Island
would see it as junk fish, and they couldn't

00:17:07.179 --> 00:17:10.429
understand why I was serving it on a three
star menu in New York City.

00:17:10.429 --> 00:17:16.600
Because fish is good. It's all up here.
A lot of it is about us stepping outside of

00:17:16.600 --> 00:17:20.110
a comfort zone, you know, and understanding
a little bit more about fish.

00:17:20.110 --> 00:17:25.110
But how can you understand and embrace fish
when they're changing their name every other

00:17:25.110 --> 00:17:29.950
day?
A popular fish that's endangered today -- or

00:17:29.950 --> 00:17:34.330
is certainly, if it's not completely endangered,
is on the path to be -- is Chilean sea bass,

00:17:34.330 --> 00:17:40.780
originally known as Patagonian toothfish.
A beautiful fish that was another marketing

00:17:40.780 --> 00:17:44.710
name-change game was Orange Roughy.
Orange Roughy, great fish.

00:17:44.710 --> 00:17:48.360
How many people have heard of Orange Roughy?
Do you know what it was called before it was

00:17:48.360 --> 00:17:50.049
Orange Roughy? Slimehead.

00:17:50.049 --> 00:17:51.049
&gt;&gt; [Laughter]

00:17:51.049 --> 00:17:54.210
Rick Moonen: That's what it was called.
Now, if you came into Oceana, and I had my

00:17:54.210 --> 00:17:57.260
captain come up to you and say, [in a French
accent] "Tonight, chef Rick Moonen has prepared

00:17:57.260 --> 00:18:01.110
the slimehead very nicely for you with blah
blah," you're not going to listen to it.

00:18:01.110 --> 00:18:05.400
So it's about, you know, that achievement
of comfort level.

00:18:05.400 --> 00:18:15.230
Oysters. They're renamed every single day.
I mean, an oyster is basically identified

00:18:15.230 --> 00:18:20.140
by where it's grown, you know, and which is
actually oysters are a great example of something

00:18:20.140 --> 00:18:25.070
that's very sustainable.
These are filtered feeding fish that clarify

00:18:25.070 --> 00:18:29.080
the water, that keep everything healthy, that
make the eel grass grow on the bottom that

00:18:29.080 --> 00:18:31.710
give the fish a place to hide.
It's an ecosystem.

00:18:31.710 --> 00:18:40.631
It's about us understanding our symbiosis
 -- our nourishing and giving back to the

00:18:40.631 --> 00:18:45.030
ecosystem that has been giving us something
that we are super-privileged to get, but we

00:18:45.030 --> 00:18:51.570
abused over so many, many years.
Cod. Let's talk about just for a second.

00:18:51.570 --> 00:18:54.900
Cod is what built America.
The reason that Europeans came over to the

00:18:54.900 --> 00:18:59.600
United States or into the Georgia's banks'
areas in the first place was, there was such

00:18:59.600 --> 00:19:04.570
a high population of cod that you could walk
across the water on their backs.

00:19:04.570 --> 00:19:11.520
Cod goes under the name haddock, hake, pollock,
ling cod, true cod, scrod -- which is, I guess

00:19:11.520 --> 00:19:19.780
just a nickname, a local colloquialism for
an immature cod -- tomcod, etc. etc. Atlantic

00:19:19.780 --> 00:19:22.410
cod, Pacific cod.
And that's just cod.

00:19:22.410 --> 00:19:26.299
Bass. The word "bass" doesn't hardly mean
anything, because it just sounds so good it

00:19:26.299 --> 00:19:34.150
gets slapped on to so many different fish.
So that's confusing layer number one.

00:19:34.150 --> 00:19:36.799
How do I tell if it's fresh?
How do I do this?

00:19:36.799 --> 00:19:41.270
You know, when I was asked to do a cookbook,
"Fish Without a Doubt," is what I came up

00:19:41.270 --> 00:19:47.350
with, because I was typecasted into being
a seafood chef because I was at Oceana, and

00:19:47.350 --> 00:19:49.630
that's what I was doing.
And now I'm outspoken.

00:19:49.630 --> 00:19:54.130
I'm a proponent of the ocean.
Trying to get people to be aware that What

00:19:54.130 --> 00:19:59.710
we eat affects the future or the possible
future of what we're going to eat.

00:19:59.710 --> 00:20:05.850
I did a little bit of research, because seafood
cookbooks generally did not sell.

00:20:05.850 --> 00:20:09.890
Because seafood is available fresh on this
coast and that coast and pretty much in the

00:20:09.890 --> 00:20:12.970
middle, not much of anything else.
And because it's so confusing that, that's

00:20:12.970 --> 00:20:16.320
the way it's always been.
The middle of America is eating meat and dairy

00:20:16.320 --> 00:20:23.260
and the sides of America are eating seafood
more, but not at a crazy rate.

00:20:23.260 --> 00:20:26.730
As time would go on, we learned more that
seafood is good for us, so we have to source

00:20:26.730 --> 00:20:31.049
it out.
And we -- there was a lot of questions about

00:20:31.049 --> 00:20:35.730
doing a seafood cookbook.
So I did a little bit of a canvas.

00:20:35.730 --> 00:20:38.832
I asked a lot of people, "Why don't you cook
seafood at home?”

00:20:38.832 --> 00:20:44.400
"Mmm. It smells up my kitchen.
I'm not really sure how to pick it out -- tell

00:20:44.400 --> 00:20:45.900
if it's fresh.
I don't know what to do with it.

00:20:45.900 --> 00:20:48.429
It's expensive.
If I don't cook it that day, it's bad the

00:20:48.429 --> 00:20:52.080
next day.
And what if I overcook it?”

00:20:52.080 --> 00:20:57.600
If you overcook it, it's just unfamiliarity.
We weren't familiar with it.

00:20:57.600 --> 00:21:00.370
Well, seafood stinks.
That's what people think.

00:21:00.370 --> 00:21:06.010
It smells up your kitchen.
Well, when I grew up in Flushing -- I'm going

00:21:06.010 --> 00:21:09.410
to go back to my childhood.
I think back on some things now. -- I think

00:21:09.410 --> 00:21:12.790
it's just a matter that we're not used to
the way it smells.

00:21:12.790 --> 00:21:16.179
Good seafood cooking isn't something that's
a normal aroma in your household.

00:21:16.179 --> 00:21:20.130
I used to deliver newspapers in these apartment
buildings.

00:21:20.130 --> 00:21:23.720
And when you're in an apartment building,
the smells of what's coming out of each little

00:21:23.720 --> 00:21:28.120
apartment is just amazing, the diversity of
 -- I mean, I was just a little kid.

00:21:28.120 --> 00:21:33.880
I was chubby. I was hungry back then.
So I was really always attracted to it all.

00:21:33.880 --> 00:21:38.570
But the reality of it is, when you come home
and there's a turkey in the oven, or there's

00:21:38.570 --> 00:21:44.140
a prime rib in the oven, no one's coming home
screaming, "Ma! It smells beefy in here.”

00:21:44.140 --> 00:21:48.679
Fish is fish. It's part of who we are.
And because it wasn't part of the American

00:21:48.679 --> 00:21:53.429
culture growing up, it was treated as something
foreign.

00:21:53.429 --> 00:21:55.410
You know, in my household, we ate it once
a week.

00:21:55.410 --> 00:21:59.440
My mother, devoted Catholic.
Fridays we're eating fish.

00:21:59.440 --> 00:22:04.370
If you eat meat on Friday, you go to hell.
So, I'm probably going to hell; I ate a hotdog

00:22:04.370 --> 00:22:07.169
once.
But, that's what it was.

00:22:07.169 --> 00:22:10.809
You know, I mean, it could be fishsticks with
coleslaw and tartar sauce one Friday, which

00:22:10.809 --> 00:22:16.230
personally, as a kid, I loved.
Could be -- or a swordfish steak broiled under

00:22:16.230 --> 00:22:19.120
the broiler.
Or a piece of salmon, or something different,

00:22:19.120 --> 00:22:23.440
but it was something delicious.
And it's just about that comfort.

00:22:23.440 --> 00:22:27.970
And it's about -- that's where I'm hoping
that our culture is ready to push ourselves

00:22:27.970 --> 00:22:31.799
over the edge and get a little bit more diverse.
Because at the end of all of this, that's

00:22:31.799 --> 00:22:33.919
the answer.
It's about diversity.

00:22:33.919 --> 00:22:38.670
It's about getting out of your little comfort
zone of shrimp, salmon, and tuna, and that's

00:22:38.670 --> 00:22:40.770
it.
Okay, I got my Omega-3s, I'm good.

00:22:40.770 --> 00:22:47.110
But the problem is that we put so much pressure
on those species that they become endangered

00:22:47.110 --> 00:22:50.500
and nonsustainable.
So somehow we're going to have to find a comfort

00:22:50.500 --> 00:22:53.870
of stepping outside that so.
I wanted to write a book to help out with

00:22:53.870 --> 00:22:59.150
that a little bit, you know?
Say that, categorically, here's a recipe,

00:22:59.150 --> 00:23:02.460
pick anything out of this category of fish,
and you'll have a success.

00:23:02.460 --> 00:23:05.200
And hopefully you're stepping out into a place,
you know.

00:23:05.200 --> 00:23:10.700
So you're having tilapia once in awhile.
You're having a barramundi.

00:23:10.700 --> 00:23:18.990
You're having fish that's outside of your
"tuna, salmon, and shrimp" box of comfort.

00:23:18.990 --> 00:23:21.570
Freshness. How do I tell if it's fresh, you
know?

00:23:21.570 --> 00:23:28.600
That I rolled into the book.
The comfort of picking out a piece of meat

00:23:28.600 --> 00:23:32.910
is not really that -- the anxiety level is
low.

00:23:32.910 --> 00:23:35.351
You know what to look for.
It's the same things when you're looking for

00:23:35.351 --> 00:23:37.380
fish.
If it's browning around the edge, or it doesn't

00:23:37.380 --> 00:23:41.590
look right, or the coloration isn't the same,
if it's not attractive to you, you've got

00:23:41.590 --> 00:23:44.220
all the basic skills.
And that's what I try to do.

00:23:44.220 --> 00:23:48.450
This language I'm speaking to you with, that's
the voice -- that's the language I wanted

00:23:48.450 --> 00:23:50.830
to do a book.
I didn't want to be pretentious on a subject

00:23:50.830 --> 00:23:53.059
that's already confusing, because that's not
going to get you anywhere.

00:23:53.059 --> 00:23:56.101
I want to say, "It's not that difficult. If
I can do it, you can do it.”

00:23:56.101 --> 00:24:00.810
And because I was doing it for so many years,
you know.

00:24:00.810 --> 00:24:05.160
I tried to kind of like give people an idea
like what's happening.

00:24:05.160 --> 00:24:08.470
How are fishes handled is really the most
crucial thing to the freshness.

00:24:08.470 --> 00:24:13.600
It's not How many hours out of the water.
Two boats fishing, same day, same bay, pulled

00:24:13.600 --> 00:24:17.100
a fish out of the water.
Ooh! They both caught a 15-pound, striped

00:24:17.100 --> 00:24:20.049
bass.
Mr. Number One, with a cigar in his mouth,

00:24:20.049 --> 00:24:24.010
throws it on the deck, steps on it, pulls
the hook out of the mouth, and starts fishing

00:24:24.010 --> 00:24:27.450
again and leaves it right there.
Second person carefully takes it out, puts

00:24:27.450 --> 00:24:31.169
it on ice, guts it, puts it there.
Fish has been out of the water for exactly

00:24:31.169 --> 00:24:32.210
same time.
Which fish is fresher?

00:24:32.210 --> 00:24:36.870
Well, the one that's on ice.
Well, not really.

00:24:36.870 --> 00:24:41.299
It's the same amount out of the water.
So it's How it's caught. It's sourcing.

00:24:41.299 --> 00:24:45.840
It's so many different things.
Oh boy, more confusion, all right?

00:24:45.840 --> 00:24:52.510
But, you can use your own eyes. You can tell.
If they're handled correctly, you know, and

00:24:52.510 --> 00:24:57.140
you can go to a fishmonger, and you ask questions.
What I want to do is empower you to ask the

00:24:57.140 --> 00:25:00.020
questions.
The more consistent questions that are asked

00:25:00.020 --> 00:25:05.120
upon an industry that has not really focused
on being consistent is going to force them

00:25:05.120 --> 00:25:09.179
to be consistent, and the power of where we
are right now can tell you that.

00:25:09.179 --> 00:25:15.780
Just walking through this campus is blowing
my mind, and this is where movements are changed.

00:25:15.780 --> 00:25:22.250
I mean, we vote with our wallets, you know?
So knowledge is incredibly powerful.

00:25:22.250 --> 00:25:25.419
And emotion behind it is what makes people
use that knowledge.

00:25:25.419 --> 00:25:29.419
So I'm here to make you all cry if I can figure
that out today.

00:25:29.419 --> 00:25:31.750
The fish, you look at it; it's supposed to
bounce back.

00:25:31.750 --> 00:25:34.760
You touch the flesh.
The scales should be all intact, the eyes

00:25:34.760 --> 00:25:37.860
should be clear.
You know, the gills should be red.

00:25:37.860 --> 00:25:41.360
All the usual things that people are a little
bit afraid to look at.

00:25:41.360 --> 00:25:45.990
But basic instinct.
Your nose [sniff] -- it should smell like

00:25:45.990 --> 00:25:47.780
an ocean.
Fish should smell like an ocean.

00:25:47.780 --> 00:25:50.620
They shouldn't have a stink; they should have
a scent, you know?

00:25:50.620 --> 00:25:59.340
A perfuminess about them.
Cucumbery, you know?

00:25:59.340 --> 00:26:03.110
Those are just a few of the concerns about
 -- Overcooking.

00:26:03.110 --> 00:26:06.940
All right.
Within the book I talk about playing with

00:26:06.940 --> 00:26:10.810
your food a little bit: prodding, touching.
You've got a set of references.

00:26:10.810 --> 00:26:13.179
Every single person here has cooked an egg
I would assume.

00:26:13.179 --> 00:26:15.520
We've all fried an egg.
We've seen an egg being fried.

00:26:15.520 --> 00:26:20.620
An egg white is pure albumin practically.
You see it go out of the eggshell.

00:26:20.620 --> 00:26:25.020
It's pure, clear, see through it, translucent.
[whistles] You know that, "Well, until that's

00:26:25.020 --> 00:26:27.090
all white, the egg whites aren't cooked."
Right?

00:26:27.090 --> 00:26:29.220
'Cause then they turn, you can't see through
them anymore.

00:26:29.220 --> 00:26:32.170
They turn white like your shirt.
And then the yolks, depending on how you want

00:26:32.170 --> 00:26:33.511
them cooked, you know what you're looking
for.

00:26:33.511 --> 00:26:37.750
You've learned what kind of egg you like.
Same thing with fish, you know?

00:26:37.750 --> 00:26:42.130
Protein, when it cooks, changes colors.
So you just need to poke and look in there

00:26:42.130 --> 00:26:46.770
a little bit, but if you put a piece of fish
in a pan, you'll notice on the bottom, it's

00:26:46.770 --> 00:26:49.590
going to start changing color.
If it's a clear fish, you know, it's got that

00:26:49.590 --> 00:26:52.890
translucence to it, little by little it's
going to start turning more white just like

00:26:52.890 --> 00:26:56.100
the egg white did.
You know, if it's pink fish, you know if it's

00:26:56.100 --> 00:26:58.679
a red fish, it turns a little lighter in color.
It turns pink.

00:26:58.679 --> 00:27:02.590
But those are your set of references.
It's all just about paying attention and having

00:27:02.590 --> 00:27:08.630
a little bit of fun with your food.
Touching.

00:27:08.630 --> 00:27:13.220
The way a raw piece of fish feels, it feels
like a raw piece of flesh.

00:27:13.220 --> 00:27:15.840
But, as it cooks, the proteins firm up a little
bit.

00:27:15.840 --> 00:27:19.610
So rule of thumb, if you touched your thumb
right here, you'd see it's nice and soft.

00:27:19.610 --> 00:27:23.809
If you touch your thumb to your index finger,
that muscle starts to tighten up a little

00:27:23.809 --> 00:27:25.820
bit.
And as you go down a little bit more, you

00:27:25.820 --> 00:27:27.280
touch this finger, the muscle firms up a little
more.

00:27:27.280 --> 00:27:29.950
That's like a medium rare piece of meat or
fish.

00:27:29.950 --> 00:27:34.080
That's more like medium. It gets firm.
And if you touch your pinky, that's as firm

00:27:34.080 --> 00:27:36.600
as it gets.
That's like a well-done piece of meat.

00:27:36.600 --> 00:27:39.420
And if you're not sure, poke your knife in
there and look at it.

00:27:39.420 --> 00:27:43.171
And little by little you learn how to tell
the doneness of a fish.

00:27:43.171 --> 00:27:48.440
So you're not going to blow it.
You're not going to ruin a piece of ocean

00:27:48.440 --> 00:27:55.530
protein by overcooking it as long as you're
willing to play around with it a little bit.

00:27:55.530 --> 00:27:59.630
And then, once you've got your set of references,
you're good.

00:27:59.630 --> 00:28:03.970
And then there's sustainability, you know?
About being responsible.

00:28:03.970 --> 00:28:12.490
"Where do I go? It gets so darn confusing.”
So I threaded sustainability through my book.

00:28:12.490 --> 00:28:15.850
What I tried to do is break it down by cooking
techniques.

00:28:15.850 --> 00:28:22.900
All right? And cooking techniques changed
a little bit over the years.

00:28:22.900 --> 00:28:28.289
My book -- 1977 is the copyright of this book.
This is a blue book that cover fell off.

00:28:28.289 --> 00:28:31.770
It's called "The Encyclopedia Of Fish Cookery,"
by A.J. McClane.

00:28:31.770 --> 00:28:38.420
And this is what I had to go to, because fish
cookery was not -- there wasn't a large section

00:28:38.420 --> 00:28:40.480
in a library on this.
And if you went through.

00:28:40.480 --> 00:28:43.750
Say you're are a house cook, and you wanted
to learn how to cook fish at home.

00:28:43.750 --> 00:28:46.250
You knew how to pick it out and you were going
to bring it home and you really wanted to

00:28:46.250 --> 00:28:47.900
know how to do it.
You had two choices.

00:28:47.900 --> 00:28:53.970
One that was old school which is old baked
casseroles, stinky bad fish, no-wonder-you-didn't-like-it

00:28:53.970 --> 00:28:58.289
recipes, you know?
Or you got recipes that you could never reproduce

00:28:58.289 --> 00:29:01.600
at home.
So it's hollandaise sauce, glissage, poached

00:29:01.600 --> 00:29:04.030
all of these other things that were just too
far ahead of it.

00:29:04.030 --> 00:29:08.669
But me as a professional, this was my set
of references.

00:29:08.669 --> 00:29:12.559
And I was funny, I was just thumbing through
it and cooking methods.

00:29:12.559 --> 00:29:18.000
Deep frying.
Basic fish batter, thin fish batter, all part

00:29:18.000 --> 00:29:20.360
of frying.
Deep frying in advance.

00:29:20.360 --> 00:29:22.980
Deep frying to order.
Deep frying, more deep frying.

00:29:22.980 --> 00:29:26.260
Oh, pan frying.
Sauteeing.

00:29:26.260 --> 00:29:30.490
Fish cakes.
Poaching or broiling.

00:29:30.490 --> 00:29:34.890
Baking and planked fish.
That's it. That's it for fish cookery.

