Or putting them into little wrapping them
into tinfoil and letting them steam with aromatics

00:29:56.780 --> 00:30:02.520
which is actually a derivative of a classic
called a fish in papyote.

00:30:02.520 --> 00:30:10.531
Grilling. There wasn't a lot of grilling or
barbecueing of fish, you know, many years

00:30:10.531 --> 00:30:13.270
ago.
And it didn't come in with the French influence,

00:30:13.270 --> 00:30:19.789
because French cuisine doesn't really embrace
grilling -- bottom grilling -- it just wasn't.

00:30:19.789 --> 00:30:25.350
So you never saw that going on in French restaurants.
And that became more of an evolution, and

00:30:25.350 --> 00:30:30.570
I was part of that.
Roasting. Slow roasting, large pieces of fish,

00:30:30.570 --> 00:30:35.360
not just baking in a casserole, but actually
taking a piece of fish, coating it in something

00:30:35.360 --> 00:30:38.500
and roasting it.
Cooking it, letting it rest, slicing it.

00:30:38.500 --> 00:30:42.710
That became more popular.
Butter-basting, where you're not just frying

00:30:42.710 --> 00:30:45.929
something, you're putting it in a pan, and
as the butter browns, you keep putting it

00:30:45.929 --> 00:30:49.490
over the top of the fish.
That's a technique that I use a lot, and I

00:30:49.490 --> 00:30:54.870
try to introduce into "Fish Without a Doubt."
The purpose of this book is to get people

00:30:54.870 --> 00:31:02.190
to take from "Dad fish" to "successful fish.”
Next book will be the fancy stuff.

00:31:02.190 --> 00:31:06.549
But I didn't want to intimidate anybody by
coming out with a book that was going to like,

00:31:06.549 --> 00:31:10.460
continue the whole idea that you, "Well, you
make a hollandaise, and then you just fold

00:31:10.460 --> 00:31:12.370
in some whipcream, and put it over the top,
and that's it.”

00:31:12.370 --> 00:31:19.480
How many people make a hollandaise at home?
None that I know of anyway.

00:31:19.480 --> 00:31:24.170
And butter poaching and better poaching methods.
Like not boiling fish.

00:31:24.170 --> 00:31:28.940
Cooking it at controlled temperatures so that
the protein actually stays intact and that

00:31:28.940 --> 00:31:34.481
the results come out unctuous.
And those are all techniques that I incorporated

00:31:34.481 --> 00:31:38.370
into the book.
And it's broken down by exactly that.

00:31:38.370 --> 00:31:46.039
And flavor combinations.
It basically gives you a matrix of possibilities,

00:31:46.039 --> 00:31:49.340
you know, so that when you're going to the
store, and you've got a recipe in your hand

00:31:49.340 --> 00:31:52.880
that you ripped out of a magazine or printed
on your computer.

00:31:52.880 --> 00:31:58.230
And you're going to the store to buy chicken
breast, broccoli, garlic, lemon grass, whatever

00:31:58.230 --> 00:32:01.550
it is, you can get those items.
But if you're going to the store, and you're

00:32:01.550 --> 00:32:07.169
going for trout, for instance.
Okay, I got a great trout recipe for all of

00:32:07.169 --> 00:32:12.539
you, all right?
It's chicken fried trout with a coleslaw and

00:32:12.539 --> 00:32:14.150
a tartar sauce.
Delicious.

00:32:14.150 --> 00:32:18.730
And you're, "Great, I'm going to go do it.”
And you run to your store and you go, "I need

00:32:18.730 --> 00:32:22.169
trout. No trout? Ohh.”
What do you do?

00:32:22.169 --> 00:32:26.250
You know you're going to find chicken.
Well, what I try to do is, accept substitutes.

00:32:26.250 --> 00:32:30.620
You know that same chicken fried trout recipe?
You can do it with tilapia.

00:32:30.620 --> 00:32:33.779
You can do it with catfish.
You can do it with mahi mahi.

00:32:33.779 --> 00:32:39.220
You can do it with Arctic char.
So you've got yourself one technique, yet

00:32:39.220 --> 00:32:47.000
a matrix of possibilities for success.
And that was another directive that I wanted

00:32:47.000 --> 00:32:48.990
too.
And that's what's going to get you comfortable

00:32:48.990 --> 00:32:54.179
 -- or hopefully, will get you comfortable
 -- with personally having success at home

00:32:54.179 --> 00:33:00.800
which will make you want to do it more and
more again and see some diversity.

00:33:00.800 --> 00:33:07.490
What really happened -- how it all came to
change was -- in my lifetime.

00:33:07.490 --> 00:33:12.320
I'm from the East Coast.
I saw when Gilbert Le Coze opened up a restaurant

00:33:12.320 --> 00:33:19.190
called La Bernadette in New York City.
It started to show people that fish can be

00:33:19.190 --> 00:33:23.860
treated a little bit differently and enjoyed.
It's okay to have fish that's not completely

00:33:23.860 --> 00:33:30.050
cooked through if it's sourced out right.
He started to introduce carpaccios and ceviches

00:33:30.050 --> 00:33:36.860
and tartars and medium-rare cooked fish.
And this is at a time where sushi wasn't even

00:33:36.860 --> 00:33:39.279
recognized.
People weren't eating raw fish.

00:33:39.279 --> 00:33:44.711
It just wasn't done.
But a restaurant in New York City got four

00:33:44.711 --> 00:33:49.419
star acclaim from New York Times, got a lot
of recognition from New York Magazine, and

00:33:49.419 --> 00:33:56.220
it started to get national -- it became a
movement of seafood shifting.

00:33:56.220 --> 00:34:03.100
People started to go, "Ooh. Something different.”
And we start to enjoy fish and seafood in

00:34:03.100 --> 00:34:09.770
a different manner.
And then, people like Julia Child came on.

00:34:09.770 --> 00:34:13.070
She had her cooking show.
And she was helping to break down.

00:34:13.070 --> 00:34:15.670
Here's this lady that everybody can embrace.
You like her.

00:34:15.670 --> 00:34:20.000
She's kind of goofy, which makes it even better,
because if you're going to talk about a pretentious

00:34:20.000 --> 00:34:24.980
subject, being goofy is kind of cool, right?
And she'd throw this fish up on the table,

00:34:24.980 --> 00:34:31.040
and it was this ugly, ugly fish called the
monk fish or an angler fish or a lotte, L-O-T-T-E.

00:34:31.040 --> 00:34:34.869
Of course, it's going to have 12 names, because
we've already had that discussion.

00:34:34.869 --> 00:34:38.390
And she goes to break it down, and you see
the little piece of the tail comes out.

00:34:38.390 --> 00:34:42.369
And the ugly thing goes away and it gets cooked
up and it's unbelievable.

00:34:42.369 --> 00:34:45.830
The recipe is great.
And it's called "Poor man's lobster," and

00:34:45.830 --> 00:34:49.260
we all embrace it.
Well, that's great.

00:34:49.260 --> 00:34:51.960
And that's a good start, but everybody ran
that way.

00:34:51.960 --> 00:34:55.871
Monk fish became so popular, that it became
overfished, all right?

00:34:55.871 --> 00:35:01.040
So, then you had Paul Prudhomme.
You know, he came on board and here's this

00:35:01.040 --> 00:35:05.910
guy from Louisiana, really cool, spicy stuff,
you know, pan-blackened red fish.

00:35:05.910 --> 00:35:11.849
And that was fantastic 'til red fish ran out.
Because we have a tendency to be, "What's

00:35:11.849 --> 00:35:17.369
next?" And we jump on board and we just fish
it to death almost.

00:35:17.369 --> 00:35:25.310
Another example of that is -- I don't even
like to talk about it -- but, it's when Japanese

00:35:25.310 --> 00:35:33.510
sushi, Japanese cuisine, the respect, the
intrigue of Japanese cuisine came into the

00:35:33.510 --> 00:35:39.710
mainstream United States eating habits.
I remember when I went to Nobu in New York

00:35:39.710 --> 00:35:41.290
City.
Awe man, it's changed.

00:35:41.290 --> 00:35:47.010
I mean, I remember when I first had hamachi
with uzu and a jalapeno pepper on it.

00:35:47.010 --> 00:35:50.760
It just made me stop and I couldn't believe
it; it was so delicious.

00:35:50.760 --> 00:35:54.619
You know, blue fin tuna.
And all of these things that are just amazing

00:35:54.619 --> 00:35:57.950
products.
Chilean sea bass is another amazing product,

00:35:57.950 --> 00:36:05.109
but we need to be able to be creative enough
to realize that chefs -- gatekeepers, influential

00:36:05.109 --> 00:36:12.750
people that are trying to introduce seafood
 -- that we're careful that we don't push

00:36:12.750 --> 00:36:15.920
things in a direction that makes them fall
off of a cliff.

00:36:15.920 --> 00:36:21.800
Because fish aren't created equal.
And when I first got involved in talking out

00:36:21.800 --> 00:36:26.940
about sustainability, it was one thing.
"Let's stop catching so many," because we've

00:36:26.940 --> 00:36:30.970
got technology.
The last 50 years, technology has far surpassed

00:36:30.970 --> 00:36:34.859
anything that's being hunted, all right?
I mean, nothing that's hunted today stands

00:36:34.859 --> 00:36:38.640
a chance.
If we allow it, they will be completely captured

00:36:38.640 --> 00:36:42.470
and just taken out of the ecosystem, and we
can't allow that to happen.

00:36:42.470 --> 00:36:46.210
Everything is here for a reason.
One thing works off another.

00:36:46.210 --> 00:36:50.300
They rely on each other.
And I like to use a car example, because people

00:36:50.300 --> 00:36:53.150
seem to care more about what they put in their
cars than in their bodies, etc.

00:36:53.150 --> 00:36:57.060
And so, would you pull your precious car to
the side of the road, open the hood, take

00:36:57.060 --> 00:37:01.700
a part out, throw it on the side, close your
hood, and expect it to drive the same? No

00:37:01.700 --> 00:37:05.490
way.
But we do that to our ecosystem, because if

00:37:05.490 --> 00:37:08.560
it doesn't affect us, we don't really care
about it.

00:37:08.560 --> 00:37:16.089
It has historically just moved on as insignificant
or not as important as it should be.

00:37:16.089 --> 00:37:20.180
You know, sharks.
Peter eventually came out with a movie called

00:37:20.180 --> 00:37:23.170
Jaws.
"Sharks are bad. I don't care if they all

00:37:23.170 --> 00:37:25.500
go away, my kids are safer.”
Well, that's not true.

00:37:25.500 --> 00:37:32.250
Sharks are a necessary part of an ecosystem.
Everything plays a role, and you can't just

00:37:32.250 --> 00:37:38.570
pull something out and expect that it's going
to continue to roll, you know, in a healthy

00:37:38.570 --> 00:37:48.150
manner.
[pause] I am confused where I'm going next

00:37:48.150 --> 00:37:55.130
to be honest with you.
Other things that I'd wanted to incorporate

00:37:55.130 --> 00:38:00.680
into "Fish Without A Doubt" is basically just
a level of comfort.

00:38:00.680 --> 00:38:06.500
You know, when I did this book, I tried to
immerse myself into what most people have

00:38:06.500 --> 00:38:11.780
to encounter as hurdles when they decide that
they're going to cook fish at home.

00:38:11.780 --> 00:38:17.700
And that is, you know, recognizing, being
comfortable going to the market, holding on

00:38:17.700 --> 00:38:22.980
to it, how to handle it when they get home.
And so, I had a lot of different sections

00:38:22.980 --> 00:38:28.990
of "Fish Without A Doubt" are just illustrative.
Rub your hand over the fish, touch it, smell

00:38:28.990 --> 00:38:33.290
it, feel it, cook it, while it's cooking,
you know, prod it.

00:38:33.290 --> 00:38:37.589
You know, here's some flavors that are going
to work, that are going to give you a much

00:38:37.589 --> 00:38:44.310
better level of success.
So back to sustainability.

00:38:44.310 --> 00:38:47.530
It wasn't just about taking too many fish
out of the ocean.

00:38:47.530 --> 00:38:52.910
And I thought that was the way it was going
to be, because there's other issues of concerns,

00:38:52.910 --> 00:38:59.320
one of them being -- not just overfishing
 -- but bycatch.

00:38:59.320 --> 00:39:04.420
Different fisheries are targeted species,
boats go out after them, and they capture

00:39:04.420 --> 00:39:10.849
a lot of fish that are not necessarily on
their targeted species list.

00:39:10.849 --> 00:39:17.510
So there's a lot of excessive waste of bycatch.
I just wanted to give a statistic.

00:39:17.510 --> 00:39:20.080
These are the accidental capture of untargeted
species.

00:39:20.080 --> 00:39:24.720
So if you're going after pollock, for instance,
in the Bering Sea, and you've got these gigantic

00:39:24.720 --> 00:39:29.820
trawlers, these things that are the size of
city blocks that are just, you know, removing

00:39:29.820 --> 00:39:36.010
pollock from an area where they've identified
them, other fish come up with them such as

00:39:36.010 --> 00:39:39.400
wild salmon, such as sea turtle such as other
things.

00:39:39.400 --> 00:39:44.070
And by the time they filtered out what they
wanted to bring up in the first place, everything

00:39:44.070 --> 00:39:50.810
else gets pushed over the side, dead or dying.
So the tuna's like 7.3 million tons in a year.

00:39:50.810 --> 00:39:58.700
That's a lot of protein.
And in an ecosystem that the biomass is just

00:39:58.700 --> 00:40:04.150
diminishing, we need to take that into consideration.
So I needed to take that into consideration.

00:40:04.150 --> 00:40:07.490
I didn't want to, but it's something that
I had to think about when I was trying to

00:40:07.490 --> 00:40:12.940
decide what I was going to put on my menu
or what I was going to promote.

00:40:12.940 --> 00:40:17.630
Habitat destruction was another one.
If you destroy where they live, you know,

00:40:17.630 --> 00:40:25.060
that's going to contribute to the deterioration
of a population of a species.

00:40:25.060 --> 00:40:32.280
So if you're going to drag these real, superheavy
nets along the bottom of the ocean floor,

00:40:32.280 --> 00:40:35.700
basically you're destroying where they live.
You're catching them, you're bringing them

00:40:35.700 --> 00:40:37.300
up.
Let's just talk about shrimp for instance,

00:40:37.300 --> 00:40:41.190
because people understand shrimp.
Shrimp dredging, you throw these big nets,

00:40:41.190 --> 00:40:45.550
and you drag them around using sonar.
"Well, there seems to be more in this area,

00:40:45.550 --> 00:40:47.970
that area.”
But you're knocking down everything that they

00:40:47.970 --> 00:40:50.990
need to reproduce after you're done catching
them.

00:40:50.990 --> 00:40:56.920
It's like clear-cutting a forest to get a
deer for dinner, and then there's no more

00:40:56.920 --> 00:40:58.800
forest left.
And you wonder why there's no more deer the

00:40:58.800 --> 00:41:05.200
next time you come back to find that deer.
Same exact mentality and it happens continuously.

00:41:05.200 --> 00:41:11.380
So habitat destruction.
So now, still trying to be a chef here and

00:41:11.380 --> 00:41:18.050
trying to figure out and do the right thing.
I've got to worry about sonar, radar, just

00:41:18.050 --> 00:41:22.241
technology being too strong.
Then now, you got to worry about them catching

00:41:22.241 --> 00:41:26.920
things they're not supposed to catch, and
that's a big disgusting waste.

00:41:26.920 --> 00:41:31.190
And now, it's about habitat destruction.
Let's stop messing up their world.

00:41:31.190 --> 00:41:34.510
Let's make sure the coral reefs are good and
everything else, so that there's a healthy

00:41:34.510 --> 00:41:37.910
ecosystem for everything else.
Good. I'm done, right? No.

00:41:37.910 --> 00:41:41.210
The thing that I thought was the greatest
answer in the world was farming fish.

00:41:41.210 --> 00:41:43.790
We could farm fish, right?
This is great.

00:41:43.790 --> 00:41:47.150
Farmed Atlantic salmon, the best thing since
sliced, white bread.

00:41:47.150 --> 00:41:51.160
This was back when I was in Oceana.
I thought farm-raised Atlantic salmon was

00:41:51.160 --> 00:41:55.550
tremendously great.
And I'm supporting these environmental groups

00:41:55.550 --> 00:41:59.030
doing efforts about, "Give Swordfish a Break.”
Fine. We'll give swordfish a break.

00:41:59.030 --> 00:42:02.510
It's worked. All right?
Now they start talking about the salmon that

00:42:02.510 --> 00:42:07.410
I've been loving, because it's inexpensive,
it's diverse, everybody loves salmon.

00:42:07.410 --> 00:42:11.800
Salmon is the number one selling fin fish.
You can cook it just about any technique you

00:42:11.800 --> 00:42:15.150
could possibly want.
It's on the cover of my book.

00:42:15.150 --> 00:42:17.540
You know, you wouldn't put something on the
cover of a book that's going to scare people

00:42:17.540 --> 00:42:23.950
away, you know? So salmon being fantastic,
I didn't want to hear how it's not good for

00:42:23.950 --> 00:42:25.480
the environment.
I'm getting to the point where I don't want

00:42:25.480 --> 00:42:29.060
to know anymore.
My job is getting much more complicated, but

00:42:29.060 --> 00:42:32.860
I needed to, because I was already deep into
finding out about what's happening.

00:42:32.860 --> 00:42:41.250
And there's aquaculture that you're raising
carnivorous fish, carnivorous animals.

00:42:41.250 --> 00:42:45.990
There's nothing you can buy in the supermarket
that's carnivorous, except for fish.

00:42:45.990 --> 00:42:48.970
Now, in order to feed those fish, you have
to give them meat.

00:42:48.970 --> 00:42:52.900
And the meat that they eat is more fish.
So you go over, and you grab larger quantities

00:42:52.900 --> 00:42:56.060
of this fish.
Sardines, anchovies, what do you care -- you

00:42:56.060 --> 00:42:58.730
don't eat them anyway, right?
Let's get all those anchovies and sardines

00:42:58.730 --> 00:43:05.099
out, make Purina Salmon Chow, feed the salmon.
Well, the ratio is off.

00:43:05.099 --> 00:43:08.170
Takes you five pounds of this fish to make
one pound of that fish.

00:43:08.170 --> 00:43:14.220
What about all the other wild species that
are relying on the sardines, anchovies categorically?

00:43:14.220 --> 00:43:17.680
They suffer too. Oh boy.
That's just what I needed.

00:43:17.680 --> 00:43:20.630
Not only that, they escape.
Because they're open nets.

00:43:20.630 --> 00:43:25.660
They put them in the ocean, you know, in these
netted areas and there's high concentrations

00:43:25.660 --> 00:43:27.560
of fish in there.
Well, they have predators.

00:43:27.560 --> 00:43:32.210
Predators come and rip holes in there.
If I was an orca whale, or if I was a killer

00:43:32.210 --> 00:43:36.540
whale, and I knew there was a smorgasbord
of salmon around the corner, [whistles] me

00:43:36.540 --> 00:43:38.970
and the rest of the boys are going to go rip
a hole in there and have dinner.

00:43:38.970 --> 00:43:41.329
Well, that happens, and millions of them escape
a year.

00:43:41.329 --> 00:43:45.020
Also competing for food.
And God forbid that they start to reproduce

00:43:45.020 --> 00:43:48.000
with the wild species.
That will just take a genetic code that has

00:43:48.000 --> 00:43:52.049
been set up over millions of years and just
pollute it to the point where they won't even

00:43:52.049 --> 00:43:54.440
 -- they'll get so confused they won't even
know where they're going anymore.

00:43:54.440 --> 00:44:04.760
Where was I? Okay.
Well, and then, there's the usage of antibiotics.

00:44:04.760 --> 00:44:08.760
You know, if you've got a concentration of
fish in such a small area, one gets sick,

00:44:08.760 --> 00:44:12.829
they all get sick.
The stress or the strain of their environment

00:44:12.829 --> 00:44:15.990
is just not right.
So, Holy Smokes.

00:44:15.990 --> 00:44:19.200
I'm giving you so many negative things.
Well, there are solutions.

00:44:19.200 --> 00:44:24.470
A permanent barrier, first and foremost, between
the farm and the natural environment would

00:44:24.470 --> 00:44:28.470
be great. Okay.
One more thing I didn't even bring up -- these

00:44:28.470 --> 00:44:35.850
nets.
Sea lice, which is a natural part of a life

00:44:35.850 --> 00:44:42.190
cycle of a fish, but normally the sea lice
don't come into their world when they're immature.

00:44:42.190 --> 00:44:44.931
When they're immature, they don't have a coating
on the outside.

00:44:44.931 --> 00:44:47.740
They don't have the scale coating that can
help protect them from sea lice.

00:44:47.740 --> 00:44:52.470
Well, these salmon farms produce such high
concentrations of sea lice that then spews

00:44:52.470 --> 00:44:58.330
into the natural environment that anything
that may swim by, such as one of the five

00:44:58.330 --> 00:45:01.109
left species of salmon, they get infected
by it.

00:45:01.109 --> 00:45:07.369
And it's detrimentally affecting their population
and their chances of coming back in consequent

00:45:07.369 --> 00:45:12.210
years.
So salmon is really a big case study right

00:45:12.210 --> 00:45:17.130
now on what's happening in aquaculture and
how there are better techniques.

00:45:17.130 --> 00:45:20.040
And the better techniques are when there's
a permanent barrier.

00:45:20.040 --> 00:45:24.710
When there's closed containment systems.
And there are -- there's a lot of research

00:45:24.710 --> 00:45:26.320
being done.
There's prototypes.

00:45:26.320 --> 00:45:31.730
It's more expensive, so no one wants to run
and do it, but -- in our world and hopefully

00:45:31.730 --> 00:45:37.040
in our lifetime -- we're going to see more
and more of closed containment systems being

00:45:37.040 --> 00:45:39.400
implemented.
They're talking about doing it in Canadian

00:45:39.400 --> 00:45:44.200
government subsidization, subsidizing some
closed-containment systems.

00:45:44.200 --> 00:45:49.590
And the one thing that I don't even like to
talk about -- but it's a part of my reality

00:45:49.590 --> 00:45:55.740
 -- it's health risks.
You know, health risks of fish.

00:45:55.740 --> 00:45:57.920
I'm trying to sell you fish.
I'm trying to tell you how good it is.

00:45:57.920 --> 00:46:02.820
Omega-3 is great for your body, for your mind,
and I want you to buy my book.

00:46:02.820 --> 00:46:07.599
I want you to take it home, because it's a
tool, you know.

00:46:07.599 --> 00:46:15.290
And then if you purchase, you know, sustainable
fish off of like programs like Seafood Watch.

00:46:15.290 --> 00:46:22.390
Seafood Watch is like this Monterey Bay Aquarium.
Well, it's not just aquarium.

00:46:22.390 --> 00:46:31.890
To me it's like the center for sustainability
of the oceans in my world, because it's a

